UObjectToolTips.ColorGradient:
- FColorGradient -

A color gradient. Sort of modeled on FRuntimeCurveLinearColor from
CurveLinearColor.h, but has a different way of storing colors and
interpolating between them. Uses an FColorCurve instead of three
separate float curves for the RGB channels.
UObjectToolTips.ColorKey:

UObjectToolTips.FortMeshNetworkEventsLoader:
@class AFortMeshNetworkEventsLoader

The main goal of this actor is to provide an event dispatching mechanism for Fortnite and
the games built off of it. Phase 1 will be events defined in the component proper, but phase 2+
will incorporate a more general framework for event responding and communication that the game/plugins
future scripting initiatives/etc can interface with, and even a state machine defining phases
and actions within a phase (see: https://docs.google.com/document/d/1v-7PzLudd9QkAQ3Bi7B2KvQ3wbSlVYGlISTGPXXA1e0/edit?usp=sharing)

We will want to support multiple loaders that can also be tied to one/many playspace(s) that way events
can target multiple events on a single map.

There are 2 types of mesh network events that can be communicated to the Root Server that are then
disseminated out to the rest of the server/clients on the network.

MeshEventBurst - i.e. MeshNetEventBurst EventName
MeshEventStart/MeshEventEnd - i.e. MeshNetEventStart EventName and MeshNetEventEnd EventName

UObjectToolTips.CreativeRoyalePlayspaceComponent_LevelRe:
@class UCreativeRoyalePlayspaceComponent_LevelReset

Reset the world between Edit mode gameplays.

 CVars

 CreativeRoyale.LevelReset.bEnableLevelReset (Off - disabled)
   Enable or disable Level Reset.

 CreativeRoyale.LevelReset.bBuildingContainersOnly (Off - disabled)
   Debug support BuildingContainers only.

 CreativeRoyale.LevelReset.bHandleBuildingDamaged (On - enabled)
   Testing Handle building damage as well as death.

 CreativeRoyale.LevelReset.bTestIgnoreFloorLootProcessing (Off - disabled)
   Debug ignore floor loot.

 CreativeRoyale.LevelReset.bRespawnDeadActorsNextStartGame (Off - disabled)
   Testing Level Reset by respawning dead actors next start round/game.

 CreativeRoyale.LevelReset.bDestroyDamagedActorsAfterEndGame (Off - disabled)
   Testing Level Reset by destroying damaged actors after end round/game.

 CreativeRoyale.LevelReset.bRemoveActorInstanceFromSave (On - enabled)
   Testing Remove ActorInstanceRecords entry from Level Save Record.

 CreativeRoyale.LevelReset.bRemoveActorFromSave (Off - disabled)
   Testing Remove just Actor entry from Level Save Record.

 CreativeRoyale.LevelReset.bUseTransientFlagForAddActorToSave (Off - disabled)
   Testing set transient flag for calls to AddActorToSave.

 CreativeRoyale.LevelReset.bSaveParentToAttachTo (On - enabled)
   Testing Save ParentToAttachTo and Restore Attached Buildings.

 At startup in the initial map, the BuildingActor / BuildingContainer Actors
   have callbacks added for OnDie / OnDamage.
 When the BuildingActor Dies during gameplay,
   (When bRespawnDeadActorsNextStartGame is true)
     it is added to list to get respawned next start round/game
   (Else)
     it is added to the Level Save Record and registered for deletion rollback.
 When the BuildingActor is Damaged during gameplay (if bHandleBuildingDamaged is true),
   (When bDestroyDamagedActorsAfterEndGame is true)
     it is added to list to get destroyed after end round/game, then added to dead list
   (Else)
        it is added to the Level Save Record and registered for modification rollback.
 When Edit mode round/gameplay is complete,
   (When bRespawnDeadActorsNextStartGame and bDestroyDamagedActorsAfterEndGame are true)
     damaged actors will be deleted and added to dead actors to be respawned at start of next round/game
   (Else)
     the Level Save Record performs the rollbacks.
     (When bRemoveActorInstanceFromSave or bRemoveActorFromSave are true)
       ActorInstanceRecords or Actors are removed from the Level Save Record.

UObjectToolTips.FortHeldObjectComponent:
@class UFortHeldObjectComponent

      The held object component defines all the necessary functions/data to allow
      an object to become a held object. The component will implicitly grab a defined
      shape component (sphere, capsule, etc) and a defined projectile movement component. With
      these components it can handle implicitly being thrown, dropped, and placed.

      The component is setup with a generic held object weapon that defines an equip "pickup" animation,
      an ability to throw the object, and an ability to place the object. Drop happens via weapon switch, death,
      etc implicitly.

      @example: Attach this component to a BuildingGameplayActor. The BGA will override CanInteract
      and call the components CanInteract. If BGA can be held it will call OnInteract and call PickupHeldObject.

      @todo: For more fine control over pickup, placing, and throwing it would be nice to define anim
      notifies that can be assigned to an animation. Right now, attachment is done on pickup via on interact
      so it doesn't fully sync up with the weapon's equip anim. Throwing happens via a trigger event on the throw
      which looks great, but the detachment is happening via a timer, which isn't great.

UObjectToolTips.ManagerParticipantSubsetID:
A FManagerParticipantSubsetID allows a single manager implementing the QuestManager interface, to manage *multiple* unique sets of
participants to which quests can be granted, by assigning unique IDs to each subset.

ID's are context specific to any given manager, but always represents a unique group of participants that granted quests can be
scoped to within the scope of that single manager.

Any single ID is not necessarily globally unique across different managers ('1' could be widely used for example by multiple
managers to represent different participant subsets - 'squad 1' for a squad manager, or 'bounty event 1' in a bounty quest manager)

The ID is implemented as a simple uint32 under the hood. FManagerParticipantSubsetID offers a variety of methods to assist in
initializing this uint32  from integer, name (hashed), or gameplay tag (hashed from string) depending on the contextual
requirements of the implementing manager

A mutator that forces players to use a given list of Cosmetic Override parts regardless of what they have equipped

Split Storm Design Doc: https://docs.google.com/document/d/1fNHt9Q4UK7RU0x5YcFIcrQrMNo33xABfXvv7GogWAb4/edit
UObjectToolTips.FortAthenaMutator_AI_SignificanceBasedUp:
A mutator used to optimize AI processing in Athena. If enabled, this mutator will batch and stagger the
tracked pawns' FortMovementComp_Character component updates so that not all components are being updated
on the same frame. The movement components are placed into buckets based on their pawn's significance. In
each bucket, movement components are divided evenly and randomly into groups (the number of groups in a
bucket equals it's FramesPerUpdate value). Only one group is updated per bucket per frame, so for a bucket
with FramesPerUpdate = 3, three groups will be created and the movement components in that bucket will be
spread evenly throughout them. Then the three groups will be updated on the next three frames (one per frame)
and the cycle will continue.

UObjectToolTips.FortDynamicRollBaseWeightTableRow:
A row in a Table that defines the base weights for items that can be rolled. This is similar to a loot table, but much simpler.
It represents a roll entry in a table of potential items to roll.
Using named weights of a loot table provides similar functionality, but has to work around specifics (ie it always adds to weights instead of replaces).
This however gives us a little more flexibility, in that we avoid duplicates and execute custom logic related to a dynamically changing loot pool.
It also provides seeded generation so that situations can be repeated and analyzed.
It also avoids needing to set up loot tiers and loot packages, which has been a blocker for creative for things in the past.
The goal of this row is to stay generic and can be used for other similar systems in the future. It was created for player augments, but has no knowledge of player augment item types.

UObjectToolTips.AthenaCapturePoint:
AAthenaCapturePoint
      This new building gameplay actor is the basis for all building based capture
      points.  The actor is setup to handle a plethora of capture point setups.

      Basic Rules: When a team (1+ players) steps on the capture point the point
      will flag which team is capturing and begin growing the percentage towards
      100%, when the point reaches 100% the point will lock for a defined set of
      time at which point it will unlock.

      CaptureStates: Idle is used when the point has no one on it but doesn't have
      the ability to return to 0. (Note: Useful when the decrease value is 0 to
      force the other team to drop it down to zero before gaining any control).
      Capturing is when a team is actively driving the percentage in their favor.
      Contested is when multiple teams are on the point forcing the point to contention
      based on the rules defined. Reseting is when the point has no one on it
      and has the ability to drive the percentage back to zero.

      Contention Rules: Currently there are two types of contention rules and it
      isn't hard to add more in the future. MajorityWins (default) is where the
      difference between multiple teams is the number of capturers and when an
      even number are present the point is in contention. (Note: This setup actually
      handles N teams where the team with the most and the team with the second
      most affect the difference, i.e. Team1 = 2, Team2 = 1, Team3 = 1 then Team1
      is capturing with a count of 1). OneTeamOnlyWins is where only 1 team can
      be present on the point at a time to actually capture it.

      Unlock Rules: Once the point is locked and the time interval is through and
      unlocks the point there are a couple of rules that govern how the point behaves.
      ResetState will remove the team that is controlling the point and reset all
      values to 0 so capturing can begin from the beginning again. MaintainState is
      used to keep the controlling team in ownership of the point at 100% so it is
      the other teams job to recapture the point back to 0 then back up to 100%.

UObjectToolTips.BuildingItemCollectorActor:
ABuildingItemCollectorActor

      The Building Item Collector Actor is a complex actor that can be used
      to build many different kinds of devices that players interact with
      and deposit items from their inventory.

      The Item Collector does not actually store actual inventory items. The
      actor simply verifies how many a player has, saves the total towards
      the deposit goal for that players team, then deletes those its from
      the players inventory.

      The Item Collector has various states (that may grow over time) such as FirstToGoal,
      FreeForAll.

      FirstToGoal - The objective of this behavior is for teams to deposit inventory items
      trying to be the first team to reach a desired goal value.
      When a team reaches the goal the Item Collector becomes "captured" and will no longer
      accept inventory drops until it is reset.

      Uses: BluGlo pylons in STW and Vending Machines in BR

UObjectToolTips.AthenaNavPresenceDetectorComponent:
ActorComponent that checks if one or more AthenaNavMesh is/are available under the owner's location.

   It will initially broadcast NavMeshPresenceDetected or NavMeshPresenceDetected to tell if there is
   proper NavMesh under owner's location (with bWasDetectedBefore/bWasUndetectedBefore = false).

   If a NavMesh is not there, it will listen to newly computed nav tiles and if ever that NavMesh
   become valid under the owner's location, we will broadcast the NavMeshPresenceDetected event once all the NavMeshes are detected (with bWasUndetectedBefore = true).

   If bDisableUponNavMeshPresence = false, if NavMesh is present, it will continue listening to newly computed nav tiles and if ever the NavMesh
   becomes INVALID under the owner's location, we will broadcast the NavMeshPresenceUndetected event (with bWasDetectedBefore = true).

   @note: if NavmeshNameToUse is None, it wills check against all existing AthenaNavMesh. See AthenaNavSystem.h for navmesh names to specific if needed.
   @note: if bDisableUponNavMeshPresence is True, the component Unregisters and so stops observing NavMesh changes and will not refire the NavMeshPresenceDetected/NavMeshPresenceUndetected events.

UObjectToolTips.FortAnalyticsEventDenylistEntry:
Allows hotfixability of analytics events. You can denylist an event for a specific PlaylistName or PlaylistType (EFortGameType).
Specify the denylist type entry, then set the playlist (or type) in the PlaylistKey member,
followed by the EventName and the probability of sending it. 0 == Never send, 1 == always send.
PlaylistNames are more specific, so take precedence over a similar entry for an event in a given playlist type.
Specified as an array to allow hotfixes to incrementally add entries to Denylist.
When loaded at runtime, these are converted to associative containers for faster lookup.

UObjectToolTips.FortAthenaMutator_InventoryOverride_Buck:
An inventory override mutator that provides Cobalt-specific round-based loadout mechanics.
Loadouts are organized into buckets
Each round, a loadout is randomly selected for each bucket, which will be used by all players assigned to that bucket.
As long as there are at least as many buckets as players-per-team, no two players on the same team be assigned to the same bucket in a given round.
Player-bucket assignments are rotated each round so that as long as there are at least as many buckets as rounds, no player should get the same bucket twice.
Every team in given round has the same set of loadouts.

An object responsible for updating dynamic weights based on in game events for a given player/bot.
This only stores the data necessary for a given player, most data is queried from the table manager to avoid unnecessary duplication.
This component also handles binding to events relevant for a specific player, to prevent the table manager from having to bind to all player events and manage those event subscriptions.

This class is intended to be generic and not tied to player augments.

UObjectToolTips.FortDamageNumbersActor:PercentDamageThre:
Array of Percent Damage Thresholds where the value of each threshold entry represents the upper value of a damage range.
     Percent Damage is considered as being in a specific Tier so long as the damage is <= the threshold value, otherwise we check the next tier,
     thus each threshold should be greater than the previous one. The number of thresholds should be one less than the number of PercentDamageColors
     so that any damage that exceeds the last threshold can be represented by the final color in PercentDamageColors.
     These thresholds can be overwritten by mutators via FortGameStateAthena_ApplyMutatorOverridesToPercentDamageThresholds.

Use this class if your object should have health, should take damage, should persist in save games, and/or should execute its own abilities.
These actors are not statically placed in levels, but instead spawned at runtime.
For example, this should be used for the propane tank or a turret.

UObjectToolTips.FortAthenaCollisionReactionComponent:OnR:
Called when a reaction happens on an actor:
- HitActor: the actor we are reacting with
- bFromAsyncSweepBox: if true this reaction comes from a sweep box, otherwise it's from a physics collision
- CollisionReactionType: the type of reaction the component is doing
- bIsFirstContinuousReactionOnDelayableActor: will be valid only if the type of reaction has a set delay (ex. PawnReactionDelayPerActor)
  If valid will be false if the actor has been reacted to during the last check, otherwise will be true if during the last check the actor was not colliding with component
  Can be used to avoid spamming client feedbacks (ex. audio) on reaction

Called when the component has been activated by a proper Mesh Network Event based on the MeshEventNames, and playspace info properly handled
       - FGameplayTag EventTag - The gameplay tag used for this mesh event activation
       - bool bPersistentOnOff - High level bool that is true for all " ON PersistentEvent Types - JIP, Start, Change" and false for the "off EventType PersistentEventEnd"
       - EEventResponderEventType EventType - Enum for the specific mesh event type that is triggered, switch on this for specific handling of JIP, Update, Burst - use bPersistentOnOff for simple on/off stately behavior
       - FString EventParameters - A string passed by the caller and handled as desired by the actor, calls have the format of "params=XYZ" where the string we will receive here is "XYZ"

To modify what determines placement, the UpdateTeams and FTeamPlacementData can be overridden to change what TeamsInfo holds.
By default, TeamsInfo will be determined using GameState->GetAllTeamInfo() and updates on AFortGameModeAthena::OnTeamScoreUpdated (and when players are removed from the game)

If a mutator is controlling the score, make sure UpdateTeams gets called when a team's score changes.

and adds functionality to make the underlying choice (new or old) more invisible to scripting.

and the fact that assets are only loaded once determined to spawn should keep it lighter.

UObjectToolTips.FortCosmeticReactivePreview:
Class for driving reactive behavior outside of a game context.

In most cases, simply proving entry points for ReactivePreviewSupportInterface is sufficient.
When a reactive needs special attention, we can derive from this class to provide the required logic.
UObjectToolTips.FortCosmeticReactivePreview_InterfaceWra:
Class for driving reactive behavior outside of a game context.

This version of the class simply calls into the interface where appropriate.

Use case Scratch (S11 SuperLevel): Implement on the CCPM
StartPreviewReactiveResponse start a progressive update from 100 - 350.
PreviewReactiveSteppedUpdate would set the material's CurrentLevel param
StopPreviewReactiveResponse cancels the timer and sets CurrentLevel back to 0.

Use case Bundles: Implement on the AnimBP
StartPreviewReactiveResponse would start a stepped update from 0 ~ 4
PreviewReactiveSteppedUpdate would update based on the input value, likely a map to trigger the damaged other vs took damage reactions...
StopPreviewReactiveResponse cancels the timer and cleans up the reactive blends

UObjectToolTips.StateTreeManagerComponent:
Component responsible for creating, running, and possibly replicating StateTrees on Actors
There will only be one of these components on an Actor and will handle any/all StateTrees requested to run on the Actor

                                          ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
                                         | StateTreeManagerComponent |
                                          ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
               Single component attached to an Actor that will run all StateTrees for said Actor
                                                      |
                                                      |
                     -------------------------------- |---------------------------------
                     |                                |                                |
          ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~          ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~          ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
            | FStateTreeRuntimeData |        | FStateTreeRuntimeData |        | FStateTreeRuntimeData |
          ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~          ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~          ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
Structures containing the runtime data required to run a UStateTreeExecutionContext (brains of the state machine)
                         and optionally replicate the state transitions to clients
                     |                                |                                |
                     |                                |                                |
                        \                             |                             /
                           \                          |                          /
                              \                       |                       /
                                 \                    |                    /
                                    \                 |                 /
                                       \              |              /
                                          \           |           /
                                             \        |        /
                                                \     |     /
                                                   \  |  /
                                                     \|/
                                           ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
                                          | FStateChangeDataArray |
                                           ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
     Single FastArray replicating all state changes/transitions for all StateTrees that want to replicate.
  These StateChanges will be put into their respective client-side simulation and sorted in transition order.
                                                      |
                                                     /|\
                                                   /  |  \
                                                /     |     \
                                             /        |        \
                                          /           |           \
                                       /              |              \
                                    /                 |                 \
                                 /                    |                    \
                              /                       |                       \
                           /                          |                          \
                        /                             |                             \
                     |                                |                                |
  ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~     ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~     ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
 | FStateTreeClientSimulationData |   | FStateTreeClientSimulationData |   | FStateTreeClientSimulationData |
  ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~     ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~     ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
Each FStateTreeRuntimeData that wants to replicate to clients will have a matching FStateTreeClientSimulationData.
The FStateChangeDataArray communicates the transitions from the FStateTreeRuntimeData to the respective
FStateTreeClientSimulationData. These transitions are queued up, wait for the associated UStateTreeTaskObjects to
replicate, and simulates the transition in the same order it happened in the FStateTreeRuntimeData's StateTree.

NOTE: UStateTreeTaskObjects is where the gameplay logic lives and are separately replicated subobjects who
themselves likely have replicated variables. These subobjects are referenced in the FStateChangeData and can't
be assumed to arrive at the same time that the transition made its way through this system; hence the queuing system.

NOTE: UStateTreeTaskObjects may never make their way to the client if the server began and ended the state it's
associated with before it could replicate to the client. In this situation, this replicated transition system will
skip that transition altogether and move forward to the next transition.

UObjectToolTips.MeshNetworkComponent:
Component that can be added to Actors in order to allow them to Receive properties from the Mesh Network
and to Send RPCs to the Mesh Network.

When added to an Actor, all of the Actors replicated properties will be replicated through the Mesh.
However, any RPCs on the Actor will behave as if no mesh was present (Server only goes to the Game Server,
Client only goes to the specific client, and Multicast only goes to clients connected to the Game
server).

Properties on the MeshNetworkComponet will be replicated alongside Actor Properties, just like standard replication.
But, MeshNetworkComponents only support Server and Multicast RPCs. Server RPCs go up through the Mesh
(and may be aggregated) and Multicast RPCs go down through the mesh to all clients. There is no notion
of (single) Client RPCs on the MeshNetworkComponent.

UObjectToolTips.FortCreativeAFKComponent:
Component that determines whether or not a player is Away From Keyboard during a creative game.

There are four "AFK States" that a player might be in:
 - Not AFK: The player is interacting with the game frequently enough that they are not considered AFK.
 - Suspected AFK: The player hasn't interacted with the game for a short time, so we start watching for signs that will prove they're not AFK.
 - Confirmed AFK: The player hasn't interacted with the game for a long time, so they are considered AFK.
 - Remained AFK: The player has been confirmed AFK for some time.

Interacting with the game in some detectable way will reset the state to "Not AFK."

This component allows an actor of any type to act as if it is attached to the primary item definition of this pick-up.
When the player picks up the pickup that owns this component the AttachedActor will become attached to the player through UFortControllerComponent_ItemAttachedActor.
This is useful in cases where we want an item definition to act like an actor when it is in a player's inventory or is stored in a pickup. The attached actor can do persistent things like show a map icon or act as an AI target.

This component allows an actor of any type to act as if it is attached to an item definition the player is carrying.
When the player drops a pickup with a matching item definition that is associated with an attached actor the attached actor will become attached to the newly spawned pickup through the pickup's UFortPickupComponent_ItemAttachedActor.
This is useful in cases where we want an item definition to act like an actor when it is in a player's inventory or is stored in a pickup. The attached actor can do persistent things like show a map icon or act as an AI target.

UObjectToolTips.CosmeticDataComponent:
Component used to track individual cosmetic properties of an arbitrary type based on the actor's equipped cosmetics.

Properties are broken up into buckets based on the slot tag (for instance, a character could have a
CosmeticSlot.Backpack and CosmeticSlot.Outfit) and have property tags (such as CosmeticProperty.BackpackColor1
and CosmeticProperty.OutfitColor2).

Properties can be of any type that is derived from FCosmeticPropertyBase so plugins can easily inject new properties.

Only one property with a given type or tag can be present in a bucket at a time. If a new property with matching
type and tag is added, that property will override the existing value.

-- This is very experimental, and could change significantly as we add more concrete use cases. Use only if you're
okay with that! --

UObjectToolTips.FortConversationMemoryComponent:
Component which wraps up a conversation memory structure and can be housed and shared between different actors as required e.g.
On NPC pawn/Actor - conversation memory (e.g. item sale stock + counts) recreated + reset whenever pawn respawns. Stock shared between all interacting players.
On NPC controller - conversation memory (e.g. item sale stock + counts) PRESERVED across pawn respawns.  Stock shared between all interacting players.
On interacting player - conversation memory (e.g. item sale stock + counts) PRESERVED across pawn respawns.  Stock counts are UNIQUE to each interacting players.

       * Require All - Every gate on this filter has to be in an open state for an objective to progress
       * Require Any - If any gate on this filter is in an opened state the objective can progress
       * Require Sequential Order - Will not allow gates to open unless the previous gate in the array is already opened,

UObjectToolTips.MutableObjectiveExtension_Gate:GateCheck:

Defines the pattern of multiple bullets. Each bullet originates from a specified muzzle socket and optional relative rotation from
    the central fire line which can vary between some min and max values. The weapon will still obey BulletsPerCartridge and if the
    BulletPattern is longer than BulletsPerCartridge, extra entries are ignored, but if it's shorter, the pattern loops back to the start.

NOTE: This pattern will overridden by OverrideBulletPattern in the corresponding FortRangedWeaponStats row for this weapon if it has a non-zero length.
UObjectToolTips.FortRangedWeaponStats:OverrideBulletPatt:
Defines the pattern of multiple bullets. Each bullet originates from a specified muzzle socket and optional relative rotation from

UObjectToolTips.FortComponent_Energy:NewActiveEnergyChan:
Energy channels that have just been added this frame.  They are guaranteed to last at least one frame, and won't
be removed until they've acted.  NOTE: Currently only EnergyChannels that are USING energy, not ADDING energy,
are put in this array.  That's because we want to guarantee we don't add and then remove in the same frame and
so dodge the energy use, but at the moment we're not concerned with exploits dodging the addition of energy.
If some use-case arises where it is an exploit to dodge adding energy, we can add those through this intermediary
as well.
UObjectToolTips.FortComponent_Energy:
Energy is an actor component that can provide energy for use by any number of users.  You can also have any number of
Energy components with unique labels to be used as separate energy pools as well.  Currently this component only
fully supports being on a pawn, but ideally we will change it to support being on a Weapon (or any other arbitrary
actor) as well.

UObjectToolTips.GasEventHistory:
GAS event history. This enables you to record events in your ASC, so that the debugger can show them in the Event History page. Follow these steps to implement this and enable that page:
1. Add one of these to your AbilitySystem component as a private member (e.g. FGasEventHistory EventHistory)
2. Implement each subclass of FGasEvent into its respective function override in your component
              (e.g. in your NotifyAbilityFailed override, create FGasEvent_NotifyAbilityFailed at the start of the function, then call Commit() at the end.)
3. Implement IGasEventHistoryProvider in your ASC, and return the event history in your GetGasEventHistory() override so the debugger can access it.
              (e.g. virtual const struct FGasEventHistoryRef GetGasEventHistory() const { return EventHistory; }

Handles BR specific implementation details of player augments. Player augments are a general purpose perk system.
BR Uses them in a specific way that may not be right for other modes such as creative.
This component handles the BR specific seasonal implementation augments. It may change from season to season.
The native class is meant to offer features that a season may opt into, or opt out of. Such as timer based granting of augments.
This initially was done in a passive ability, but because ability activation/deactivation is tied to pawn life time, some features may need to exist external to the passive ability.

UObjectToolTips.FortAimAssist2D_InputParams:
Humanlike Aim Assist Explainer
https://docs.google.com/document/d/1V44INYjCQPXuYJaR4YtctPVDEm9wo1nYOems4vDiBfU/edit?usp=sharing

Even at the highest competitive level, human players have a reaction time that has a big impact on their target acquisition and tracking.

Aim assist (including ours, currently) typically does not model this. This gives aim assist users an inhuman advantage:
       * They acquire targets accidentally when they happen to appear around corners
       * They keep their aim on targets impossibly well when they appear, change movement direction, or when a closer target dies
Therefore, this "robotic" aim assist keeps players' aim on targets longer, meaning they land more shots and do damage in a way that
is impossible for players who don't use aim assist (mainly mouse, but also gyro).

This puts us in the impossible position of making aim assist weak enough that its robotic effects don't feel unfair, but strong enough
to help players (particularly new players) enjoy the game with a controller.

"Humanlike" aim assist (as opposed to the "robotic" standard) models a human reaction time very simply, letting us tune competitive fairness
(modelled reaction time) mostly separately from player comfort (aim assist strength). Like humans do, humanlike aim assist predicts the
target's current position and velocity from older information. That prediction reaction time, and the time windows over which target velocity
and acceleration, can be tuned with the CVars:
       AimAssist2D.ReactionTime,
       AimAssist2D.VelocityEstimationDelta,
       AimAssist2D.UseEstimatedAcceleration, and
       AimAssist2D.PredictDeadTargets.

They are all inactive unless:
       * AimAssist2D.ReactionTime > 0, and
       * the rollback AimAssistModelsHumanReactionTime is enabled

This rollback is disabled for now but can be enabled at any time for testing.

The meat of the implementation is in GetPredictedPosition, which tracks a target's historical position and uses that to predict a current
position and velocity. This could also be used for beginner-friendly auto-aim systems (high reaction time = low competitiveness) and
bots (tune reaction time for difficulty; let typical human-against-human movement strategies perform well against bots).

UObjectToolTips.AIPawnSignificanceBasedMovementUpdateBuc:
Keeps track of a group of movement components and how many frames have passed since they were updated
last. A single bucket will have a number of groups equal to its FramesPerUpdate value. Only one group
per bucket is updated on a single frame, with the updated group changing each frame to achieve a
staggered AI pawn character movement update pattern.
UObjectToolTips.FabricSignificanceBasedUpdateBucket: Keeps track of all fabric objects tracked for significance relevant to this bucket. Bucket is divided into update groups for tick
UObjectToolTips.AIPawnSignificanceBasedMovementUpdateBuc:
Keeps track of all movement components whose pawn's significance falls within a certain range. All
components in a bucket will update with the same frequency (i.e. one update per FramesPerUpdate
frames) but they will be split into groups that are staggered onto different frames (i.e. a bucket
with FramesPerUpdate = 3 will have 3 groups with all components in the bucket spread equally
throughout them, and only one group will update per frame).

UObjectToolTips.FortLiveSpectatorController:
Live spectators are spectators which are connected to a live game.
Currently they exist in 2 forms - broadcast spectators and friend spectators.
Broadcast spectators have access to lots of additional information while friend spectators are a very restricted
version which are limited to just their friend's PoV. Need to be mindful of what is shared between them.

UObjectToolTips.FortAthenaMutator_RespawnAndSpectateSele:
Mutator that shows a UI menu where dead players can choose to spectate respawn targets and choose which respawn target to respawn near.

This mutator keeps a list of Respawn Targets which are actors where players can respawn at. Normally players can respawn on any enabled respawn target that their team has access to, and there is no limit to how many players can respawn at one respawn target.
Respawn targets can be added/removed at anytime.
Respawn targets must be added on the server, there are 2 ways to add them:
 1) By turning on flags like bAllowRespawnOnLivingTeammates and bAllowRespawnOnLivingSquadmates which will automatically generate specific respawn targets,
 2) By manually adding respawn locations using AddRespawnTargetData()
Once added respawn targets persist until the game is over or they are manually removed from the server by calling: RemoveRespawnTargetData()

To use this mutator you will need to add a widget derived from RespawnAndSpectateContainerWidget to the Playlist. This widget will act as the UI for this mutator.

You can implemenmt special respawning location/transform rules by making a class implement IRespawnAndSpectateSelectManager and then using SetManager() to set it to manage this class

When implementing this class you will probably want to use AddRespawnTargetData() to add at least 1 default respawn target for each team at all times. This respawn target can be shared among all teams or it can be specific to 1 team.
Multiple default respawn targets are possible, but not advised (there is no randomization so one would become the effective default while the other might never get used that way).
The default respawn target should be a replicated and always relevant actor that is at a location it is always viable for a player of the corresponding team to respawn at.
The default respawn target is set by using AddRespawnTargetData(InputData) where InputData.bShouldBeSelectedByDefault == true.
The default respawn target is used:
    1) to set the player's spectate target if they do NOT have a spectate target or the player's spectate target has becomes invalid (this often happens with player disconnects/death).
 2) when the player has waited on the respawn screen so long that they are forced to respawn, if they do NOT have a valid spectate target they will respawn at the default respawn target.

   NOTE: The console command cheat "RespawnScreenToggleMakeAllRespawnTargetsAvailableToAllPlayers" is very useful for testing. It makes the screen function correctly with just 1 player where normally you would need multiple players on 1 squad or 1 team.

UObjectToolTips.FortAthenaMutator_DestroyActorsAndCompon:
Mutator used for specifying actors and components to destroy, and when.
This can be useful for blocking functionality or improving performance, by removing
actors/components that are not utilized or are deemed non-critical for an LTM or special event.
Actors are processed for destruction at these points in time:
 1. [All preexisting actors] AFortAthenaMutator_DestroyActorsAndComponents::BeginPlay().
 2. [Placed actors only] FWorldDelegates::LevelAddedToWorld, which we bind our OnLevelAddedToWorld() to.
 3. [Spawned actors only] UWorld::OnActorSpawned, which we bind our OnActorSpawned() to.
 4. [Server] Upon enabling/reenabling a corresponding ActorDefinition with SetActorDefinitionsEnabled().
 5. [Client] OnRep_ActorDefinitions(), after enabling/reenabling an ActorDefinition on the server.
Components created dynamically after any of the above cases are not currently monitored for,
as there is not an on-component-created delegate to bind to, and periodic checks could be costly.

Note: for typical fast burst weapons, this should probably be left false for performance, false only activates the ranged ability once per burst.
But for slow bursting weapons, setting this to true will activate the ranged weapon ability per shot.
Muzzle FX (PlayWeaponFireFX) is played from ranged ability activation gameplaycue (AFortWeapon::GameplayCue_Weapons_Activation). This allows for a muzzle effect per burst shot

     accessed during the all EQSActorSpawners' SpawnActorPlacementQuery EQS if that SpawnActorPlacementQuery uses the UFortQueryGenerator_MutatorBaseQueryResults generator.

UObjectToolTips.CreativeDataChannelEvent:TriggerConditio:
Optional string that affects whether this instance of the event should generate a FireMessageOnChannel.
If it is not an expected value, it will not fire.
"Always" means it will fire no matter our past state.
"Once" means it will fire if no event with this name exists in our cache.
"OnParameterChange" means it will fire if the event is not in our cache, or if the cached Parameters is different from this instance of the event.

UObjectToolTips.DestroyActorsAndComponentsMutator_ActorD:
Passed to the bNetForce parameter of AActor::Destroy().  If true, destroy the actor regardless of Role or bNetTemporary.
Normally defaults to false in the Destroy() function.
We default to true, so that networked, non-NetTemporary actors are permitted to be destroyed on client.
For example, if it were false, and bDestroyActorOnServer/Client were both true, we might succeed at destroying a placed actor
on the server.  However, the destruction might not replicate, and our attempt to Destroy() on the client might fail.
We will log an error for any failure to destroy.
See how bNetForce is used in UWorld::DestroyActor().
Specifically, if bNetForce = false, and bNetTemporary = false, the client will fail to destroy.

UObjectToolTips.FabricSteppedPreviewFXComponent:PICDGene:
Per Instance Custom Data Index for a generic float value. Many devices will have a piece of data they want to express in the instance material.
For example,
 - A Progressor device might want to specify a float for the progression position
 - A Note Sequencer might want to specify a float for the length of a sustain.
 - A Drum Sequencer could use it for the starting index for it's per-track note data.
 - A Step Modulator might want to feed in the stepped knob's value.

Be sure this is a valid index with the NumCustomDataFloats property.

UObjectToolTips.FortAthenaPickRandomMontageStateTreeTask:
Picks a random Montage from a list.
Each Config has a weight that is used to decide how likely is for a montage to be picked.
Ex. if you have:
- montage A, weight 1
- montage B, weight 2
Montage A will have 33.33% to get picked (1/(1+2)) and Montage B will have a 66.66% to get picked (2/(1+2)).

Note: as most of the tasks, this will keep running forever until a transition happens.

UObjectToolTips.SpecialEventGameUserSettingsControllerCo:
PlayerController component that can be used in persistent special events
to save client-authoritative progression data via the local GameUserSettings.
This would allow a player to leave the event, return at a later time,
and have various objects be restored to their previous state.
Each type of gameplay object that saves its state is responsible
for restoring its state to match the save data.

Provides a mapping from a gameplay tag to a property.
Originally added for AI to allow Goal Selection EQS queries to lookup a
gameplay tag query on the owner pawn to run on possible goals that
specifies what types of items the AI is interested in. Allows making shared
sets of properties such as all "herbivores" being provided the same component.

UObjectToolTips.FortVehicleModInstanceDataComponent:
Provides a place to track dynamically spawned vehicle mod data for a given vehicle.
In some cases, changes made to a vehicle by a vehicle mod need to be tracked to meet design needs.
Such changes are tracked and used here. It is provided as an actor component so that any replication needs are easily handled.
eg instead of continuously spawning BGAs, reapplying a mod can heal already spawned BGAs to avoid spawning overhead.
In general this component should track data, rather than modifying vehicle handling logic.
One component is spawned for each applied mod using the vehicle mod config system.

UObjectToolTips.FortKeyframedMovementComponent:
Provides teleportation and simple keyframe-based animation for an actor with network replication.
At a high level, the server instance of this component provides play/stop/pause control and teleportation
The animation data is replicated to the client, as are commands. Each tracks a current animation timestamp
and uses that to evaluate the animation track each frame

FUTURE DEV NOTE (FORT-517807): A player standing on a moving platform animated with this API may jitter. This hasn't been fully investigated,
but may be caused by not communicating the implied velocity of the platform to the camera smoothing/prediction system or to the
character itself.

UObjectToolTips.BuildingPoolHarvestResourceSpawnsCompone:
Server only ABuildingSMActor component that is added to buildings we are currently pooling the harvest resource spawns for.
    When a building actor decides it wants to pool harvest resource spawns it should do the following:
            1) call UBuildingPoolHarvestResourceSpawnsComponent::FindOrAddBuildingPoolHarvestResourceSpawnsComponent() to find or create the necessary component.
            2) on the returned component call PoolAttemptSpawnResources() which will add to the amount of pooled harvest resources to spawn.
    For a short time any pooled resources will be tallied up on a per building per instigating pawn basis and at the end of that period (or the death or the building or the destruction of the pawn) the pooled resources will be spawned as a single resource drop.

Server only, AFortPoiVolume*s with tags defined in CenterSafezonesOnPOITag used to set up the current AFortGameModeAthena::SafezoneLocations.

UObjectToolTips.SlidingControlParams:LevelSlideStartBoos: Sliding: An extra impulse magnitude to apply in the 2D velocity direction when starting to slide on a level plane.
UObjectToolTips.SlidingControlParams:UphillSlideStartBoo: Sliding: An extra impulse magnitude to apply in the 2D velocity direction when starting to slide uphill at MaxSlidingSlopeAngle or higher.

UObjectToolTips.SlidingControlParams:SlidingLandingSpeed: Sliding: Landing speed transfer ratio based on fall velocity
UObjectToolTips.SlidingControlParams:SlidingFatigueMaxCo: Sliding: Max count for the sliding fatigue just to make sure it never goes overboard, this will end up stopping the character anyway, but it will prevent spamming this and getting out of control
UObjectToolTips.SlidingControlParams:DownhillGroundFrict: Sliding: Multiplier applied to ground friction when sliding downhill at MaxSlidingSlopeAngle or higher.
UObjectToolTips.SlidingControlParams:BoostLevelGroundFri: Sliding: Multiplier applied to ground friction when sliding on a level plane.
UObjectToolTips.SlidingControlParams:LevelGroundFriction: Sliding: Multiplier applied to ground friction when sliding on a level plane.
UObjectToolTips.SlidingControlParams:BoostUphillGroundFr: Sliding: Multiplier applied to ground friction when sliding uphill at MaxSlidingSlopeAngle or higher.
UObjectToolTips.SlidingControlParams:UphillGroundFrictio: Sliding: Multiplier applied to ground friction when sliding uphill at MaxSlidingSlopeAngle or higher.
UObjectToolTips.SlidingControlParams:BrakingDeceleration: Sliding: Overrides the braking deceleration while sliding.
UObjectToolTips.SlidingControlParams:WalkableFloorAngle: Sliding: Overrides the maximum angle in degrees of a walkable surface while sliding.
UObjectToolTips.SlidingControlParams:MinAnalogSpeed: Sliding: Overrides the min analog speed from the thumbstick allowed during sliding.
UObjectToolTips.SlidingControlParams:SlopeUpAddedFrictio: Sliding: The amount of friction to add at very high slope up angle
UObjectToolTips.SlidingControlParams:SlidingFatigueDurat: Sliding: The amount of time in seconds after a slide ends during which sliding fatigue will apply for subsequent slides.
UObjectToolTips.SlidingControlParams:CrouchCooldownAfter: Sliding: The amount of time in seconds after a slide ends naturally during which crouching and sliding will be prevented.
UObjectToolTips.SlidingControlParams:SlidingVerticalVelo: Sliding: The amount of vertical velocity maintained when falling
UObjectToolTips.SlidingControlParams:JumpSlideCapsuleRad:
Sliding: The detection range in front of the capsule in units of the current capsule radius. For instance if the capsule is 30cm and
this value is 3, the detection range will be 90cm from the front edge of the capsule.
UObjectToolTips.SlidingControlParams:FallingGracePeriod: Sliding: The grace time period we allow before we start falling when there are no ground in sliding
UObjectToolTips.SlidingControlParams:MaxAdditionalMoment: Sliding: The maximum additional momentum to add when going down slope
UObjectToolTips.SlidingControlParams:MaxBackwardSlidingA: Sliding: The maximum amount of backward acceleration that will be applied with input controls while sliding. Used to slow down while sliding.
UObjectToolTips.SlidingControlParams:MaxForwardSlidingAc: Sliding: The maximum amount of forward acceleration that will be applied with input controls while sliding. Used to speed up while sliding.
UObjectToolTips.SlidingControlParams:MaxLateralSlidingAc: Sliding: The maximum amount of lateral acceleration that will be applied with input controls while sliding. Used to maneuver side to side while sliding.
UObjectToolTips.SlidingControlParams:JumpSlideAllowedSur: Sliding: The maximum angle deviation in degrees from world up for a surface to be a valid jump slide candidate.
UObjectToolTips.SlidingControlParams:MaxRotationAngleOnA: Sliding: The maximum rotation angle we allow when turning with acceleration
UObjectToolTips.SlidingControlParams:MaxSlidingSlopeAngl:
Sliding: The maximum slope angle magnitude (measured from horizontal) after which friction changes will be clamped.
                      This angle is used for both uphill and downhill limits.
UObjectToolTips.SlidingControlParams:MaxForwardSlidingSp: Sliding: The maximum speed in the forward movement direction that can be reached while sliding.
UObjectToolTips.SlidingControlParams:MaxLateralSlidingSp: Sliding: The maximum speed perpendicular to the forward movement direction that can be reached while sliding.
UObjectToolTips.SlidingControlParams:MinAdditionalMoment: Sliding: The minimum additional momentum to add when going down slope
UObjectToolTips.SlidingControlParams:MinAngleForAddition: Sliding: The minimum angle to start adding downward momentum
UObjectToolTips.SlidingControlParams:MinAccelerationSlid: Sliding: The minimum angle we want on the acceleration from the current movement direction to consider this a push to drift
UObjectToolTips.SlidingControlParams:JumpSlideCapsuleHei:
Sliding: The minimum clearance height as measured from the top of the capsule to the slide surface as a percentage of the scaled capsule height.
For instance if the scaled capsule height were 100cm and the clearance coefficient were 0.4, the surface to slide on must be at least 40 cm below
the current top of the capsule.
UObjectToolTips.SlidingControlParams:MinSpeedToStartSlid: Sliding: The minimum speed before which the sliding input will put the character into the sliding mode.
UObjectToolTips.SlidingControlParams:MinSpeedToStartJump: Sliding: The minimum speed that the character must be currently moving in order to initiate a jump slide.
UObjectToolTips.SlidingControlParams:MinForwardSlidingSp: Sliding: The minimum speed threshold in the forward movement direction that can be reached while sliding before automatically exiting the sliding mode.
UObjectToolTips.SlidingControlParams:SlidingUseSlopeAngl: Sliding: The ratio between using the slope to transfer vertical velocity or just transfering to directly (0.0f means transfer directly, 1.0 means use slope to transfer)
UObjectToolTips.SlidingControlParams:SlidingRentryFromJu: Sliding: The ratio penalty to add to the speed if we land in sliding after jumping from sliding
UObjectToolTips.SlidingControlParams:LandingVelocityRedu: Sliding: The reduction of velocity we want to apply when landing in slide when going over the walking max speed
UObjectToolTips.SlidingControlParams:RotationAngleSpeedO: Sliding: The rotation angle speed we use when rotating velocity using acceleration
UObjectToolTips.SlidingControlParams:SlopeUpAddedFrictio: Sliding: The slope up angle threshold at which we start adding extra friction
UObjectToolTips.SlidingControlParams:UseAccelerationRota: Sliding: Use the acceleration as a rotation on the velocity instead of adding it to the current velocity
UObjectToolTips.SlidingControlParams:bUsePhysicsSlidingD: Sliding: Use the physics code to apply downward slope impulsion
UObjectToolTips.SlidingControlParams:SlidingIsEnabled: Sliding: Whether or not sliding is enabled. A value of 0.0 will disable sliding. A value of 1.0 or any other value will enable sliding.
UObjectToolTips.SlidingControlParams:EnterSlideFromFallI: Sliding: While falling, a slide will be automatically started upon landing if the input has been triggered within this time window before landing.
UObjectToolTips.SlidingControlParams:SlidingFatigueMulti: Sliding: While sliding fatigue is active, each slide will have its ground friction multiplied by this value. The multiplication operation will compound for each additional slide during slide fatigue.

              harshly.

UObjectToolTips.UserOptionDefinitionStringMetaData:Allow:
Specifies which characters are allowed in the value. If empty, any character is allowed.

It can contain single characters and also ranges of characters. They all go one after another with no special separators between them.
Characters - and \ must be escaped like this: \- and \\

Examples:
      "aT._" <-- Letters 'a' and 'T', dot and underscore.
      "a-zT._" <-- Any lowercase letter, letter 'T', dot and underscore.
      "a-zA-Z0-9._" <-- Any lowercase and uppercase letter, any digit, dot and underscore.
      "a-zA-Z0-9\-\\._" <-- Any lowercase and uppercase letter, any digit, minus sign, backslash, dot and underscore.

UObjectToolTips.FortPartyMemberRepData:PackedState:
State variables that can be packed together into a single struct. The current backend party service has limits on the
number of fields a party member can have (32) as well as how large each field can be (2500 bytes). To ensure we stay
under the 32 field limit, basic state variables with small values (bools, enums, etc) can be packed into a single field.
State variables that change often (such as NumAthenaPlayersLeft below) should be excluded since it would require sending
copies of all values in this struct on each update with the current implementation.

UObjectToolTips.UIStateSettings:StateLoadTimeout:
States will wait up to this many seconds for their Components to load when transitioning in.
If any Component takes longer than this then the transition will proceed and an error will be logged.
This is to prevent unhandled errors in any State Components from soft-locking the game.
UObjectToolTips.UIStateSettings:StateUnloadTimeout:
States will wait up to this many seconds for their Components to unload when transitioning out.
If any Component takes longer than this then the transition will proceed and an error will be logged.
This is to prevent unhandled errors in any State Components from soft-locking the game.

Struct for storing a player's quickbar information at time of death, for the purpose of restoring it on respawn.
Necessary in cases where the quickbar is temporarily altered between death and respawn.
For example, when spectating another player, the spectated player's items are temporarily placed
in the dead local player's quickbar.  When the quickbar is restored in lower-level code, the items are in the order

UObjectToolTips.FortGameplayCueNotify_Loop:
THIS REPLACES FortGameplayCueNotify_Looping
   This is the standard Fort GameplayCue Notify for all looping, duration based cues.
   Anything that has a duration: a distinct start and stop which is defined by the game and not the gameplay cue's assets should use this class.

   Additional features can be built into this class. Anything that is standard and easily defined completey in data is a good candidate. Any new
   thing added should fit into the Application/Looping/Recurring/Removal categories. (E.g., do NOT make new categories or put things outside the
   existing stucture of this class).

   Naming within this class diverges a bit from the rest of the gameplay cue system. For example WhileActive is referred to as Looping within the class.
   These names were chosen as they make the most sense to the FX creators on the development team. Any designer facing features should use these names.

UObjectToolTips.FortDynamicRollBaseWeightTableRow:ModTag:
Tags that weight modifier table can target to change the weight of this entry in some way. Example would be putting an item in a "group" and defining the group with a tag.
This is an array rather than a tag container, as array allows us to specify the parent tag to receive one modification, and the child tag (of that parent tag) to receive a separate modification.
Which is not possible with a standard container, since only 1 will be tag will be selectable (the parent or a child of that parent).

UObjectToolTips.FortControllerComponent_AugmentGrantingS:
The Component responsible for augment granting.

//#todo #augments matt.stone revisit this after we have finalized and make sure the comment is true to the actual system.
High level how it works:
        Server
                The server is authoritative on what augments a player can choose.
                        For prototyping, there is a passive GA that randomly chooses augment choices, and gives them to this component for the flow to start.
                        This is pending change, but perhaps it is a good high level way to let design configure augment granting, while leaving most business logic to code.
                It will replicate down to the client the choices it can make, and how many augments it has available.
        Client
                Client gets notified it has available augments and enters a granting flow.
                With augments available, the client can use input to start a selection process, where they pick the augment they want from the available choices.
                        this is currently done via a weapon item; which lets us configure camera modes, etc, while in the augment grant mode.
                Client confirms the choice and lets the server know via server RPC; the server validates and replicates new data to the client.
                Client updates it flow state based on the replicated data from the server (eg new choices, number of pending granting augments)

This AugmentGrantingSystem is intentionally decoupled from the augment component.
Thoughts on the decoupling into separate systems:
        benefits:
                Decoupling keeps the augment system separate from logic granting augments, leading to a more flexible system.
                Decoupling allows us to support different schemes of augment granting without muddying up the actual augment system with code related to obtaining.
                Decoupling allows us to have multiple granting schemes, if needed in the future. It may make sense to have multiple schemes here. But this focuses on choosing from a selection of augments.
                Decoupling means if players obtaining augments via a boss drop in the world, picking up that augment will be separate from this granting management.
                Decoupling means we can have weighted loot tables making augments available, or something else entirely providing the selection of augments available.
                The spytech system was previous investigated for augments, but found that the coupling to round based granting logic made it less flexible (there were other issues as well, such as the type of items spytech was).
                Decoupling means creative can leverage augments without the granting logic; since they will be using their own custom logic.
        negatives:
                it might be slightly more involved to figure out what you need to modify if a change is needed (but I think it shouldn't be too bad, as this keeps classes small).
                we have multiple components where as we could have only 1 without decoupling.
                it could get involved if different components have bad interactions, and need to make components interact with each other (realistically though I think not, since granting augment is done via inventory, these components will hopefully be mutually exclusive).
.

UObjectToolTips.ObjectiveFilter:
The FObjectiveFilter baseclass represents the must-have aspects of any objective filter.  The things common between
all objective filters is that there will Always be an Author that an objective will relate to.
For example, if you shoot someone, 'you' are the instigator of the objective. Inversely if the objective
is Take Damage, and 'you' take damage, you are the instigator for taking damage, even though you are not
the necessarily the damage causer.
UObjectToolTips.ObjectiveSubjectTags:
The FObjectiveSubjectTags structure provides a way to place all the filtering related components of a subject
together. Filters may have other types of conditions that might relate to certain subjects, but each subject
filter will always provide one instance of this to be used to filter against the subject in the processor.

that allows designers to specify that this subject is valid for objective progression.

UObjectToolTips.FortAthenaMutator_AI_SignificanceBasedUp:
The buckets that AI pawn's movement components will be divided into for staggered updates based on distance from the player.

    NOTE: Please ensure every value from 0.0 to 500.0 (the distances at which a pawn is assigned a significance
    value - see UFortSignificanceManager::BucketData) fits inside the range [MinDistanceFromPlayer, MaxDistanceFromPlayer]
    for at least one bucket in SignificanceBasedMovementUpdateBuckets.

    Movement components with distances that don't fit into any bucket will be managed by the game state and will not be managed
    by this mutator again, regardless of if their distance to the player changes to a value that fits into a bucket.

UObjectToolTips.FortClientMarkerRequest:
The full FFortWorldMarkerData class provides too many opportunities for a bad actor
to replicate bad information to other clients since we trust the client a lot of generating
marker data, therefore the FFortClientMarkerRequest minimizes that risk by only sending the
most basic of marker info, and then it's on the onus of the server to rebuild the correct marker
data to replicate from the clients by using the actor to determine what data it needs.

UObjectToolTips.FortWeaponRanged:AimPitchMax:
The maximum aim pitch allowed.
     Limits how high a shot can be fired. Could be used for a mortar style weapon and/or and can prevent shots from being fired straight up or even backwards.
     This can ensure that projectiles are fired with a heading that is near the camera's/muzzle's forward heading.
     (Common situations where a projectile's heading is far from expectations: 1) If the weapon is aimed very near straight up/down where a small amount of spread can radically change the projectile heading, or 2) Where ProjectilePitchOffset can cause the projectile to be fired at a pitch more than 90 degrees from 0 which essentially reverses the heading.)
     For projectile weapons: when aim pitch is clamped ProjectilePitchOffset is taken into account before clamping.
     Set >= 180 to disable.
     Data validation will fail is NOT AimPitchMin <= AimPitchMax.

The maximum difference in heading angle allowed between the muzzle aim direction and the camera aim direction.
     The muzzle aim heading will be clamped to be within this range.
     This feature is useful for making sure projectiles / ray trace bullets are fired straight down the camera even if the player is aiming at something very close to the screen while the muzzle is far from the camera center.

UObjectToolTips.FortWeaponRanged:AimPitchMin:
The minimum aim pitch allowed.
     Limits how low a shot can be fired. Could be used for a mortar style weapon and/or can prevent shots from being fired straight down or even backwards.
     This can ensure that projectiles are fired with a heading that is near the camera's/muzzle's forward heading.
     (Common situations where a projectile's heading is far from expectations: 1) If the weapon is aimed very near straight up/down where a small amount of spread can radically change the projectile heading, or 2) Where ProjectilePitchOffset can cause the projectile to be fired at a pitch more than 90 degrees from 0 which essentially reverses the heading.)
     For projectile weapons: when aim pitch is clamped ProjectilePitchOffset is taken into account before clamping.
     Set <= -180 to disable.
     Data validation will fail is NOT AimPitchMin <= AimPitchMax.

UObjectToolTips.ApplyWrapVariantDef:MetaTags:
The set of meta tags this variant specifies.
Used in LTMs which want to apply custom part overrides (Wick/Bounty)

MetaTags are applied with the main cosmetic definition tags as a base.
Any currently active MetaTags can either add additional tags or remove tags.
All active variants can remove/add tags (processed in a loop)

Use Cases:
             Variant of Peely with a painted-on suit.
                     (Remove ExtremelyUnique, add Assassin)
                     Results in Bounty leaving the skin alone (ignore that we do that anyway).

             Variant of Reaper, but he's wearing golf attire (or something).
                     (Remove Assassin)
                     Results in Bounty forcing that variant into a suit (as per any other outfit).
                     Reaper's primary variant would keep his suit.

@see MetaTags on the main cosmetic item definition (scroll up).

UObjectToolTips.RiderComponent:RiderPropAttachSoftBounds:
The soft bounds to apply to the attachment of the prop (and rider).
              If the distance between the rider and ridable props is greater than
              these bounds, it will apply offsets to the attachments based on
              the separation distance as it falls between soft and hard bounds,
              scaled by the soft bounds scalar.

              For example, if soft bounds is 2.5 and the scalar is 0.5...at a
              separation distance of 3.5, it will apply an offset of 0.5. (e.g. (3.5 - 2.5) * 0.5).

UObjectToolTips.PFWExample_ServiceWrapper_Settings:
These are the settings of service. The settings are used to initialize the service. They are also used to uniquely identify a
service inside the persistence framework. The framework can have more than instance of the same class of service wrappers as long as
their settings are different.
So a service wrapper inside the persistence framework is uniquely identified by combination of its class and its settings.
For example in the case of inventory you can have many wrappers, as long as they all have a different VK project ID, which is their setting.

In this example I am just using a simple setting of a FString.

UObjectToolTips.PlayspaceLogic:

will be enabled/disabled by manually broadcasting player entered/exited events from SkyfireControllerComponent and
will not be enabled/disabled by any actor/player actually entering or exiting the volume. Though this class implements

UObjectToolTips.UnicornDriver:
This class will drive the unicorn process - being the central point of storage for information on players, as well as their highlights
Each player is given a log, which will record their movements, build events, eliminations/deaths etc
When an elimination occurs, the Driver will log it down, and then use a series of Evaluators to determine how interesting the elimination is
Each evaluator will judge the elimination based off the player's Log, and the elimination information available
Each evaluator will judge the elimination and give it a score based off what they are interested in, and when such a highlight clip should start and stop
Evaluators combine their assessment of an EvaluatedElimination, and a highlight clip is created from it
Highlight clips are saved to a players log. Any highlight clips that are close together get merged together
At the end of the game, the server extracts an significant highlights according to what BaseHighlightExtractors are enabled
Highlight extractors make new highlight clips, or look at existing ones and say "I don't care about the score, this is an important clip!"
The server gathers all highlight clips from all players, and sorts them based off score (what the evaluators say about an interesting kill) and significance (what the Extractors say)
The top N game highlights are made into replay camera shots, and saved to the replay file

UObjectToolTips.FortAthenaMutator_CenterSafeZonesOnAircr:
This mutator overrides the default safe zone location selection behavior so the safe zones can be
individually centered along the centerline of opposing aircraft. Safe zones locations are chosen
naively with this mutator (i.e. minimal rejection, no force distances) and safe zones that are not
centered along the center path will be placed randomly according to the RejectRadius and the
RejectOuterDistance as defined by the normal safe zone configuration. Safe zones are only centered
if there are two or more aircraft in the mode, otherwise normal safe zone calculation is applied.
UObjectToolTips.FortAthenaMutator_SpawnInVehicle:
This mutator places players into vehicles that are either spawned or are already being driven by a teammate.
Placing a player in a vehicle can either be done by manually calling the PlacePawnInVehicle or automatically when the pawn is loaded.
If the player is placed in a vehicle automatically, they will be put in a vehicle at the location they loaded in if no teammates are available.

UObjectToolTips.FortVersionedSparseClassData:
This struct is to be used in any sparse class data structs that want to support
      versioning for moving data into the sparse class data more than once.  In order
      to use this, sublcasses will need to define the following static const inline...

      static const inline FFortSparseClassDataVersionInfo VersionInfo{TEXT("MyStructName"), 1};

      As well, you will need to add the function in the classes that use the versioned sparse class data...

      FORTNITEGAME_API virtual void MoveDataToSparseClassDataStructCustom(bool bIsSaving = false) const;

      This function will need to be called in MoveDataToSparseClassDataStruct, passing in false. And also
      called in PreSave, passing in true.

      Each time a child class adds more data, it will need to increase the version number in the VersionInfo.
      For an example of how to use this, please look at ABuildingActor and FBuildingActorClassData, along with
      all of it's subclasses.  For further questions, please reach out to @andrew.thayer.

UObjectToolTips.FortEvenlySizedSegment:
This structure contains a list of evenly sized segments, meaning their end points are roughly "evenly spaced" along the trail constituted by the PathToDestination points.
It also contains the necessary info for calculating and setting up the associated spline mesh and its associated collision.
This is not replicated.  It is written to be initialized and kept only on the client as the client received points in PathToDestination from the server.
While the points that make up the spline are meant to be static, there is some handling of interpolation of the end point, growth alphas, etc.

This structure can also be thought of as representing a section of the spline the length of EvenlySpacedPointsDistance (defined in AFortSplineGroundPath)

UObjectToolTips.FortThreatVisualsManager:StormWindDirect: ThreatVisuals handles creating 'storm winds' for encounters; these winds cover the area from the far side of the threat clouds to the opposite side of the encounter goals.  This angle is the value in degrees to be added on either side of the area that should be considered a cardinal direction when trying to find clouds in those directions.  We need additional angle because the clouds are on a grid formed over where the rifts form, and those are already random and may be near the edge of the relevant cone.
UObjectToolTips.FortThreatVisualsManager:StormWindActive: ThreatVisuals handles creating 'storm winds' for encounters; these winds cover the area from the far side of the threat clouds to the opposite side of the encounter goals.  This magnitude is the percentage strength (0-1) of the wind in the storm area when the clouds are active.
UObjectToolTips.FortThreatVisualsManager:StormWindInacti: ThreatVisuals handles creating 'storm winds' for encounters; these winds cover the area from the far side of the threat clouds to the opposite side of the encounter goals.  This magnitude is the percentage strength (0-1) of the wind in the storm area when the clouds are inactive.

UObjectToolTips.FortThreatVisualsManager:StormWindDesire: ThreatVisuals handles creating 'storm winds' for encounters; these winds cover the area from the far side of the threat clouds to the opposite side of the encounter goals.  This time is time in seconds over which the wind will change whenever a change occurs (such as when clouds form, when they activate or deactivate, and when they die. UObjectToolTips.VehicleModBuildingGameplayActorAttachmen:
Toggable shapes in this collection will ignore landscape collision when activated.
      Ideally this contains very little if any shapes. But may be necessary for game feel reasons.
      Strive for only 1 shape being added here for ideal perf; if many shapes are used by a vehicle mod -- that may suggest a performance concern for other reasons.
      Designers should consider each shape added here as having some performance cost as physics contacts will need to ensure they are not between a shape in this collection and landscape.
      Please consult a programmer before adding to this if you're unsure about performance concerns.

UObjectToolTips.FortAttachableProjectileComponent:
UFortAttachableProjectileComponent:
Component to support projectiles that attach to their target. The attachment must be initiated by the projectile's
authority calling AuthorityAttachToActor typically in blueprint in response to the OnTouched event. The the attachment
params are replicated to other nodes. The exact attachment location is determined separately on each client based on
the hit location and the client's animation state. The attachment location on the server will be the target's origin.
This component can be used with AFortProjectileBase (which does uses the server side capsule collision volume for
initial hit detection), or the newer AFortProjectileAthena (which offers more precise hit detection using the owning
player's mesh collision volume). Any other actor class with a ProjectileMovementComponent can utilize this component
for basic projectile attachment functionality.
The logic for this component is mostly ported from AFortAttachableProjectileDeprecated, which is now deprecated in
favor of this component. The motivation for pulling the logic into a component was to allow it to be shared amongst
different projectile actor types.
Note that if we notice attachment latency especially with client side predicted or athena projectiles, we can refine
this algorithm. All attachment is initiated server side at the moment.

UObjectToolTips.ETasksOverFramesSchedulePriorityCategory:
UTasksOverFramesScheduleManager.cpp: A manager to split work over multiple
frames to reduce frame hitches.  Any function can be added to this queue
and it will be called back based when frame time is available, likely within
a few frames.

The manager uses a priority queue to decide on what to work on next.
Priority is determined by a Category (feel free to add more) and a
SubPriority     within that Priority.  The SubPriority can be different
depending on the category.  For some it might be based on how visible
something is to the camera for example, for others some other heuristic might
be used.

There are various ways to configure TasksOverFramesScheduleManager with CVars.
See CVars in the CPP.

Note the complexity of this class is the result of trying to make sure we cover future use
such as cases:
 - Reentrant functions where a callback tries to do work in a callback
 - Lifetime of objects who own the function pointer
 - Making sure we don't accidentally skip a callback call by replacing it
 - Doing work immediately if we are still within the budget so we can see things a frame
 - earlier
 - Preventing users from accidentally making a copy of the handle

=============================================================================// List of priorities types the higher in the list the higher the priority

UObjectToolTips.FortProjectileMoveComp_Slider:Suspension:
Used to convert changes in upward speed to changes in suspension tension. SuspensionTensionToSpeedScalar * 1uu/seconds == 1 tension unit.
     Set to 0.0 to disable suspension.
     When enabled the suspension system will add tension when the projectile is deflected and loses/gains upward velocity.
     When the suspension system has tension, tension will be removed every frame in TickComponent() and velocity will be added in the opposite direction. This allows the system to mitigate bounces and small curbs acting like ramps.

UObjectToolTips.FortVisibilityManagerComponent:
VisibilityManager

      This manager handles looping through all visibility infos and checking if each
      observer can see that info and if so marks the info and syncs it to all clients.

      The visibility manager has a 1 to 1 relationship to the visibility components. A
      component will automatically register its owner actor with the manager and if the
      component is marked for observing then that actor will be registered as an observer
      too. This is normally reserved for Players, and if we have almost everything observers
      we should change this tech a bit...

      ObserverArray - The list of observers that all info's check against.
      VisibilityInfoArray - The array of infos that are sync'ed to the clients indicating an
                                                Actors visibility.

We copy all of the settings from the actor's corresponding DayPhasePostProcessComponent[] entry into this
identical component with a lower priority so that we can use it when transitioning from the last phase back to

need it is Night->Morning.)  For that reason, for Morning (which needs no duplicate), LowPriPostProcessComponent
is null.

UObjectToolTips.FortControllerComponent_RealitySapling:b:
When a sapling is spawned at match start from persistent data, the spawn EQS may adjust the sapling's spawn location from the stored persistent location if the
stored location is not valid (eg, too many other saplings nearby, inside a building, etc).
If true, the sapling's stored persistent location will be updated each match with the actual sapling's location from that match.
(If the persistent location is invalid, the new valid location will be stored. The EQS wills still test location validity each match in case the new location becomes invalid.)
If false, the sapling's stored persistent location will remain the original planted location. (If the persistent location is invalid, the EQS will find a valid location each match.)

UObjectToolTips.FortMovementComp_Character:FallingSlopeS:
When hitting a slope this angle or shallower, it's safe to slide on. Apply falling damage (if any) and reset falling height to player location at time of impact.
Steeper slopes than this angle do not cause damage until the player hits a harder impact or lands (so will do more damage at the bottom).
If you want generous sliding, set the angle to be high. Sliding commences and continues to reset the height until landing.
Falls from a high altitude will still damage you on impact of the slope if it is shallower.
(Note: 0 = horizontal, 90 = vertical. 0 disables this behavior. 90 allows sliding down any slope for no damage. Characters can normally walk up slopes < 45 degrees).
